\par 
\par 
\par It should be noticed that considerable "float" time exists in Activities B. C. and E., and because these are not critical activities, their start time may be altered as convenient within the float times.  It must be borne in mind, however, that a non-critical activity can become critical if it exceeds its float time, and in that case, the critical path must be redrawn to take this into account.  
\par 
\par It should be realised that the foregoing problem and its solution are very simple when compared with the multitude of activities that go on in a major and complex project, but the principle remains the same.  Because of the great number of activities in some projects, a computer program is set up to solve the inter-acting events and activities.  To try to do this manually would be far too laborious and time-consuming.  However, it is not the purpose of this chapter to engage in computer programming; mention is made of this phase of work in order to warn the student that C.P.M. is not a simple method of planning!
